Class SessionManager

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IMessageSink, IComponent, IEndOfDayPerformer, IExceptionListener, IFIXListener, IFIXMessageProcessor, IFIXSource, ISessionManager, IHasAttributes, IConfigurable, IRegisterable, IMessageListener, IMessageProcessor, IMessageSource, ICatalysEventListener, Cloneable, Runnable, EventListener

    public class SessionManager
extends FIXSourceListenerBase
implements ISessionManager, IMessageSink, Runnable
    Standard implementation of ISessionManager.

    Fires the following events:

    • All events of associated Session objects.
    • ICatalysEventType.SESSION_MANAGER_UPDATED_PENDING_IN_SEQ_NUM
    • ICatalysEventType.SESSION_MANAGER_UPDATED_PENDING_OUT_SEQ_NUM
    • ICatalysEventType.SESSION_MANAGER_ACTIVE_STATUS

    SessionManager/ConnectionManager interaction.

    The session manager handles all messages on a logged on session. If the session manager loses its logged on session because the session is logged out or the connection is lost, it terminates its processing thread and control passes to its connection manager.

    The connection manager handles making a connection, creating a session and logging onto that session. Once it has successfully logged on to a session, it hands over control to its session manager.

      • connectSession

        public void connectSession(boolean connect,
                           String reason)
                    throws Exception
        Attempts to connect or disconnect a session.

        If connect is true, this will make every attempt to connect to the session, irrespective of whether a session is normally scheduled for this time or not. However, if the session is blocked (see isBlocked()) an exception is thrown.

        If connect is false, this will try to cleanly terminate the session by sending a logout message. Note that this is a cleaner way to shutdown than dropSession() which just drops any connection.

        Specified by:
        connectSession in interface ISessionManager
        Parameters:
        connect - Connect if true, disconnect if false.
        reason - Text explaining reason for connect/disconnect. May be null.
        Throws:
        FatalProtocolException - if we are blocked.
        Exception - TBD

      • isOutsideSchedule

        public Boolean isOutsideSchedule()
        Returns true if my connectionPoint is outside the normal times when we would expect it to be connected, false if inside schedule, or null if we don't know (because Scheduling is not licensed or not configured).

        This is determined by looking in the scheduler for the past scheduled start and stop tasks. If the closest past task that was scheduled is the stop task, then it is assumed that we should not currently be connected. If it is the start task, it is assumed that we should.

        If Scheduling is not licensed, no scheduler is active, or no stop/start tasks exist, then this always returns null.

        Specified by:
        isOutsideSchedule in interface ISessionManager
        Returns:
        True if our connectionPoint is not currently expected to be connected.

      • setPendingSession

        public void setPendingSession(Session pendingSession)
        Informs SessionManager that we are in the process of trying to log on to the given session.

        The session manager does not take over control of this session at this point - it simply listens to its events so that it can monitor what is going on.

        Once the session has been fully accepted and logged on, control may be passed to the session manager using setSession(com.camerontec.catalys.core.session.Session, com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage).

        Specified by:
        setPendingSession in interface ISessionManager
        Parameters:
        pendingSession - Session to be monitored.

      • setSession

        public void setSession(Session newSession,
                       IFIXMessage message)
        Description copied from interface: ISessionManager
        Passes a session to be managed.

        If it is not null, the session should be connected and logged on. The message that identified the session is passed in. Normally this will be a Logon message. However, it may not be if the session was already in a logged on state.

        The session may be null, in which case the manager has no session to manage.

        If the manager is currently managing another session, that session will be terminated abruptly - that is, no Logout message is sent. The session AND its associated connection is simply closed.

        Specified by:
        setSession in interface ISessionManager
        Parameters:
        newSession - Null or a logged on session.
        message - The other party's message which identified this session. Usually a Logon message. May be null if session is null.

      • setTimerecorder

        public void setTimerecorder(IAccumulator timerecorder)
        Description copied from interface: ISessionManager
        Associate timing recording with this session.

        The actual timing instrumentation is delegated down to the associated Session object. The recording takes place following the writing of each FIX message out over a FIX connection. The difference between current time and any time stamp on the written message is recorded.

        Specified by:
        setTimerecorder in interface ISessionManager
        Parameters:
        timerecorder - object used to accumulate timing data based on message timestamps.

      • setTimestamping

        public void setTimestamping(boolean value)
        Description copied from interface: ISessionManager
        If timestamping is enabled, each message read from a FIX connection is immediately timestamped with the current time using System.nanoTime().

        The actual time stamping is delegated down to the MessageAssembler of the associated Session object.

        Specified by:
        setTimestamping in interface ISessionManager
        Parameters:
        value - True to enable time stamping mode, false to disable it (the default).

      • setSendIOExceptionStoreCondition

        public void setSendIOExceptionStoreCondition(Condition sendIOExceptionStoreCondition)
        By default a message is discarded on IOException and exception is thrown. The storeCondition can be set if it is required not to discard already persisted message on IO exception. This is only supported/applied for message that is instance of the @link com.camerontec.util.datamodel.Message. The stored(persisted) message will be re-send as part of reply to ResendRequest. NOTE: On IOException the message that do not satisfy the storeCondition is replaced with placeholder and exception is thrown. There is some inconsistency for sent message that is not received by other side. This messages is re-send. If requirement is to reject those messages as well application need to configure session customizer.
        Parameters:

      • setBlocked

        public void setBlocked(boolean blocked)
        A blocked connection point will never connect. The blocked state will be persisted if a persister is configured for that session.

        A client session will never initiate a connection while blocked.

        A server session will reject any incoming connection attempts while blocked.

        Note that blocking an active session will not automatically disconnect that session - it will just mark it as blocked so that no future connections are made. You should use the connectSession(boolean, java.lang.String) method to connect or disconnect a session.

        Specified by:
        setBlocked in interface ISessionManager
        Parameters:
        blocked - True if blocked.

      • setLocked

        public void setLocked(boolean locked)
        A locked connection point will never connect. The locked state is never persisted and will be lost when the server restarts.

        A client session will never initiate a connection while locked.

        A server session will reject any incoming connection attempts while locked.

        Note that locking an active session will not automatically disconnect that session - it will just mark it as locked so that no future connections are made. You should use the connectSession(boolean, java.lang.String) method to connect or disconnect a session.

        Specified by:
        setLocked in interface ISessionManager
        Parameters:
        locked - True if locked.

        public boolean setComponentActive(boolean active)
                           throws Exception
        The SessionManager is activated at startup unless the application is a backup in a High Availability cluster.

        This method is also called when an application in a high availability cluster moves between primary and backup status.
